<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Easter Islanders Strike for Land, Representation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Easter Islanders Strike for Land, Representation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2106130894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2132 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2106130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 20 Jun (EFE) -- The 2,800 inhabitants of 
Easter Island, a Chilean possession in the Pacific Ocean located 
3,600 km from the continent, are on strike as of 20 June 
demanding the recovery of their land from the Chilean Government 
and a senator and a deputy to represent them in Congress. 
  The afternoon newspaper LA SEGUNDA reported today that the 
strike was called for by the Rapa Nui Elders Council and 
conveyed in a letter addressed to island Governor Jacobo Hey. 
  The peaceful strike will continue until a direct dialogue is 
held with the Chilean Government to solve a number of conflicts 
affecting the island community, according to a note released by 
the strikers. 
  Easter Island, in a tropical climate, lives on tourism 
generated by the presence of 867 statues that represent gigantic 
figures of up to 20 meters high called "moais," placed in 
ceremonial temples called "ahu," which make this territory look 
like an open-air archaeological museum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

