<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-120 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prosecutor General's Office Investigates Wiretapping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prosecutor General's Office Investigates Wiretapping </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1706204394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2320 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1706204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 16 Jun (EFE) -- The Colombian 
Prosecutor General's office announced today it is conducting 
investigations of the telephone tapping discovered in the office 
of Liberal Party presidential candidate Ernesto Samper. 
  This organization received "a microphone for transmitting 
conversations and a wiretapping device," which were found on 9 
June, from Samper's campaign office. "The Prosecutor General's 
Office is conducting the investigations and technical tests 
required to establish the criminal action and responsible 
parties," Ana Lucia Obregon of the Press and Information Office 
announced. 
  The Colombian "Watergate" gave rise to a serious controversy 
on Thursday when Horacio Serpa Uribe, one of the members of 
Samper's presidential campaign, accused "the Pastranistas" 
(reference to supporters of Conservative Party presidential 
candidate Andres Pastrana Arango) of being responsible. 
  The reaction of Pastrana and members of his electoral 
campaign followed. They accused Serpa Uribe of "slander" and of 
using the strategy of "lies in view of their fear of the support 
received by the Conservative Party candidate" throughout the 
country. "They are inventing many things out of fear," a member 
of Pastrana's electoral campaign stated. 
  Fernando Botero Zea, chief of Samper's electoral campaign, 
reiterated that "only the Prosecutor General's Office can 
determine who the spies are," emphasizing that "we do not have 
any evidence." According to Botero Zea, the police released a 
report to Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff, "giving a 
detailed account of how the incident took place." 
  Political circles of the two parties are hoping the results 
of the investigation by the Prosecutor General's Office will 
conclude before this coming Sunday's elections when Samper and 
Pastrana will face one another in the runoff elections for the 
Colombian Presidency. 
  The National Civil Registry Office, charged with organizing 
the elections, reported today that it distributed 18 million 
voting cards throughout the country and that 72 hours before the 
elections, which will take place between 0800 and 1600 (1300 and 
2100 GMT), "everything is perfectly controlled." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34608 </DOCNO>
