<H3> <TI>   Strike Halts 85 Percent of Domestic Airline Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strike Halts 85 Percent of Domestic Airline Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106212794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 1730 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2106212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Midday Television Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Domestic air travel has been complicated by a pilots 
strike. A total of 85 percent of domestic operations have been 
suspended and the economic effects of the strike are already 
being felt. 
  Here is Jaime Garcia, chief of operations at the El Dorado 
International Airport in Santa Fe de Bogota, on the emergency 
plan that is being implemented today in the nation's airports. 
  [Begin Garcia recording] The emergency plan in the airports 
is being implemented by some airlines that are cooperating to 
enable passengers to reach their destinations. The domestic 
airlines cooperating are Intercontinental de Aviacion and Islena 
de Aviacion, Satena, and there are a few Aires flights. [end 
recording] 
  Intercontinental de Aviacion today covered its normal 
routes, 
that is, from Santa Fe de Bogota to Cali, Popayan, Barranquilla, 
and San Andres, among others, for a total of 19 daily flights. 
Likewise, there are 19 other flights from other cities to Santa 
Fe de Bogota. Islena de Aviacion is operating special routes 
from Santa Fe de Bogota to Cali, Medellin, and San Andres. 
  Nevertheless, 80 percent of the nation's passengers travel 
on 
Avianca, and this company does not have agreements for the 
transfer of passengers. Therefore, if you have an Avianca 
ticket and decide to travel on another airline, you will most 
likely have to purchase a new ticket. Meanwhile, Ases and 
Avianca announced they have hired foreign pilots to fly their 
international routes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

