<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows 45 Percent Support Fujimori </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows 45 Percent Support Fujimori </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2106142994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1541 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2106142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 20 Jun (EFE) -- According to the Apoyo polling 
firm, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori enjoys the support of 
45 percent of Peruvians while former UN Secretary General Javier 
Perez de Cuellar, who still has not decided whether to run in 
the 1995 elections, has only 25 percent. 
  The poll results disclosed on 19 June during a political 
television program also mention that Lima Mayor Ricardo Belmont, 
who already has launched his candidacy, enjoys 11 percent 
support. 
  According to the same source, former President Fernando 
Belaunde has the support of 4 percent; former Senator Javier 
Balle Riestra, 3 percent; and former Mayor Luis Caceres 
Velazquez, 1 percent. 
  In the case of a second round of elections between Fujimori 
and Perez de Cuellar, Fujimori would get 49 percent and Perez de 
Cuellar 37 percent. 
  If the second round were to pit Fujimori against Belmont, 
the 
results would be 55 percent for Fujimori and 27 percent for 
Belmont, according to the results of this early poll. 

</TEXT>

