<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   MAS Deputy on Subsidizing Intervened Banks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MAS Deputy on Subsidizing Intervened Banks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106133194 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2106133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] MAS [Movement Toward Socialism] Deputy Julio 
Castillo, a member of the congressional Permanent Finance 
Commission, has said it would be a serious mistake for the 
government to continue subsidizing intervened banks. He said the 
financial assistance granted thus far is equivalent to 
approximately half of the next national budget. 
  According to Castillo, the financial assistance granted thus 
far to banks experiencing problems of liquidity had unleashed 
the inflation process, which is the usual consequence of 
releasing inorganic funds into a weakened economy such as 
Venezuela's. Castillo said his party will ask the executive 
branch to step up the process of reopening the intervened banks 
so they can pay their depositors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

