<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2006161194 </F>
<F P=103> PY2006161194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 16 
June. 
  According to the Central Bank, the central government 
registered a $15 million deficit in April compared with a $24 
million surplus in the same month last year. Tax revenues 
declined 2.2 percent and export earnings fell 5 percent due to 
tariffs cuts. The government's surplus in the first four months 
of the year shrank to $14.1 million compared with the $103 
million surplus in the same period in 1993. The reason is that 
government spending increased 11.7 percent in real terms in the 
first four months of the year compared with the same period last 
year. Social security expenditures, which represent 41.3 percent 
of the government's current expenditures, showed the highest 
increase -- 23 percent. Investments rose 45 percent, totaling 
$120 million in four months. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO 
in Spanish 6 Jun 94 p 9) 
  In its Monetary Balance released on 3 June, the Central 
Bank, 
BCU, reported that its net international reserves have 
maintained the rate of growth registered since July 1993 with 
the exception of November 1993. They increased $21.2 million in 
May, thus totaling $1.28 billion. This performance indicates 
that despite the growing trade deficit the balance of payments 
continues to show a surplus, which amounted to $78 million in 
May. The two main factors that accounted for the rise in 
reserves were a $35 million increase in banking system deposits 
in the BCU and the net purchase of $23.5 million in foreign 
exchange by the BCU. Despite the increase in net international 
reserves in May, the BCU foreign exchange position registered a 
$4.5 million contraction last month, declining to $44.6 million. 
The BCU Monetary Balance also reported that the money supply 
contracted in May due to a reduction in net domestic credit, 
which was prompted by the increase in the banking system 
deposits in the BCU. (Montevideo BUSQUEDA in Spanish 9 Jun 94 p 
31) 
  Industrial production was down 18.1 percent in the first 
quarter of the year. Excluding oil refining, which has been 
paralyzed since April 1993, the contraction in industrial 
production was 5.9 percent by volume. The sharpest decline was 
in "chemical substances," mainly due to the aforementioned 
paralyzation. The drop in the employment rate is seen in both 
the 12.6 percent decline in hours worked as well as the 13.6 
percent shrinkage in hired workers. This is especially 
significant in the "textiles, garments, and leather industry." 
(Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 9 Jun 94 Market Indicators 
Section p 1) 
  The BCU reported on 3 June that Uruguay's net external debt 
decreased 3.7 percent to $1.838 billion in the first quarter of 
the year due to an increase in international reserves. The gross 
debt, however, increased $77 million, totaling $4.369 billion at 
the end of March. Liabilities in the nonfinancial public sector 
were $3.7466 billion. Loans to the central government and 
government-owned enterprises accounted for more than half this 
amount while liabilities from the issuance of public securities 
in foreign currency accounted for the remaining $1.558 billion. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 13 Jun 94 p 9) 

</TEXT>

