<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Declares State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Declares State of Emergency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2206022494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0120 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2206022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 21 Jun (EFE) -- Ecuadoran President Sixto 
Duran Ballen today decreed a national state of emergency after 
the Confederation of Indian Nationalities of Ecuador (Conaie) 
rejected a proposal to create a joint commission to draft a Land 
Development Law reforms package. Just before the official 
suspension of constitutional rights, the president had said "the 
situation in several cities was no longer bearable." 
  Peasant and Indian demonstrations began on 13 June, right 
after President Duran Ballen signed the new land law into 
effect. The demonstrators erected roadblocks on many of the 
countries roads and highways, looted businesses in several 
cities, and clashed with authorities resulting in at least three 
Indians dead and a dozen wounded. 
  During a meeting between Duran Ballen and Conaie leaders on 
Monday, the president said he would not repeal the law. Instead 
he proposed the formation of a joint commission to reform the 
law and to draw up the regulations that will govern its 
enforcement. The Indians, who make up about 30 to 50 percent of 
the country's total population of 10 million, finally rejected 
the proposals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

