<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canadian Minister, Lage Open Economic Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canadian Minister, Lage Open Economic Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2106152994 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2106152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "First Thing" program] </F>
  [Text] Christine Stewart, Canada's minister of state for 
Latin America and Africa, supported Canada's investments in Cuba 
during her address to the conference organized by the British 
publication THE ECONOMIST in Havana. The conference, called the 
Second Round Table Conference With the Government in Havana, 
officially opens its two-day closed door meetings today, 21 
June. The conference was inaugurated by Carlos Lage, vice 
president of the council of ministers, Christine Stewart, and an 
executive of the sponsoring publication. 
  Stewart stressed that Canada's government supports an 
increase in investments in Cuba, not only because they 
contribute to Cuba's development but because they are beneficial 
to Canada. 
  Currently, Canada has a significant presence in the foreign 
investments made in the Cuban mining sector, not only in the 
traditional nickel sector but also in the new explorations for 
gold, lead, and copper, as well as in the operation of oil 
fields. Stewart expressed Canada's readiness to stimulate, even 
more, the influx of capital to Cuba. 
  Ottawa announced that it will aid in the development of 
Cuba, 
as well as through the World Food Program, sending an emergency 
$360,000 [country of currency not specified] -- $720,000 in 1995 
-- in food aid to Cuba. 

</TEXT>

