<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2206144794 </F>
<F P=103> PA2206144794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Panamanian economic developments monitored through 21 
June. 
  Trade activities between Panama and Taiwan reached 
approximately $350 million in 1993, making Panama the second 
leading market for Taiwanese exports. Trade between the two 
nations is expected to increase to approximately $370 million 
this year. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 17 June 94 p 17 A) 
  Based on the behavior of the leading economic indicators 
during the first four months of the year, no significant changes 
are expected in the export levels of traditional products 
compared to figures obtained in 1993. Nontraditional exports, 
which already total $190 million, have experienced an increase 
in amount, value, and variety. The export of services for 1994 
will experience a 5-percent increase if current figures prevail. 
Duty-free zone activities will grow, but not as much as in 
1993, and the volume of oil carried by pipeline will decrease as 
anticipated. A growth in tourism will remain moderate. 
Concerning imports, the collection of tariffs and sales taxes 
indicate a 15-percent increase. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA 
in Spanish 17 June 94 p 8 A) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

