<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2206145094 </F>
<F P=103> PA2206145094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Guatemalan economic developments monitored through 21 
June. 
  Finance Minister Ana de Molina said on 15 June the directors 
of the Paris Club set September as the deadline for Congress to 
approve renegotiation of the debt. If the debt is not 
renegotiated by then, the exemptions and advantages previously 
negotiated with the Paris Club members will be canceled, and 
Guatemala's image abroad will deteriorate. (Guatemala City 
SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 16 June 94 p 6) 
  Willy Zapata, president of the Bank of Guatemala, said on 15 
June there is no reason to believe that a depreciation of the 
currency will occur at this point or that there will be currency 
exchange problems during the year, because the mechanisms the 
Bank of Guatemala has implemented are yielding positive results. 
(Guatemala City LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 16 June 94 p 4) 
  The Spanish Government has expressed its support for 
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio's government by accepting the 
total payment of $115 million for the debt incurred when the 
plant Celgusa was built. In order to pay this debt, the plant 
will be sold for U.S. Treasury bonds. (Guatemala City SIGLO 
VEINTIUNO in Spanish 17 June 94 p 5) 

</TEXT>

