<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defunct Radar Opens Upper Huallaga to Trafficking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defunct Radar Opens Upper Huallaga to Trafficking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2206161494 Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 11 Jun 94 p A14 </F>
<F P=103> PY2206161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL COMERCIO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Defunct U.S. radar installations have permitted 
Colombian and Peruvian drug traffickers to once again collect 
drugs in the Upper Huallaga valley, from where they "moved" some 
years ago when the FAP [Peruvian Air Force] began operations 
there. 
  Proof of this is a seizure by Dinandro [Antidrug Division] 
of 
537 kg of cocaine base, weapons, and communications equipment on 
5 June in Biabo district, Bellavista province, San Martin 
department. Biabo, which is on the left bank of the Huallaga 
River, 6 km from Bellavista, had been free of traffickers. The 
traffickers are said to have returned to the area. An individual 
known as "Lucho Tulon" might be one of the big shots. 
  The drugs, weapons, and communications equipment were buried 
in three "cellars" -- a type of silo -- some 500 meters from a 
house that had been raided. This is one of the most important 
events, following the seizure of 3,500 kg of cocaine base in 
Boca Manu, El Diamante, Madre de Dios, and in Inapari. 
  Actions by the Army and the Antidrug Division (Dinandro) of 
the PNP [Peruvian National Police] in coca producing areas in 
Apurimac, Ayacucho, Pasco, and Madre de Dios has helped to drive 
traffickers to Upper Huallaga. 
  As is known, when FAP Tucano planes began operations in 
1992, 
the interception of Colombian traffickers' planes was 
intensified. Some 200 small planes and civil planes are known to 
have been intercepted in coca growing areas since the start of 
FAP operations. 
  FAP Tucano planes operated from illegal airstrips in the 
jungle, helped by the U.S. radar installations in Yurimaguas, 
and the Orion and AWACS planes. 
  As of May, however, the United States suspended radar 
operations leaving FAP Tucano planes without classified 
information to help intercept traffickers' planes. The 
traffickers took advantage of this and have resumed their 
illegal work in the Huallaga region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34708 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat121_r_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Cartels Increase Flights to Huallaga </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colombian Cartels Increase Flights to Huallaga </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2206172094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1144 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2206172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 21 Jun (EFE) -- A military source reported 
today that, following the suspension in May of U.S. logistic 
support to combat the transportation of cocaine by air, 
trafficking in Peru has regained what it lost over the past 
couple of years. 
  The source added that drug mafias have increased their 
flights. He said they resumed operating in the Huallaga Valley 
from where they were forced to withdraw in 1993 in view of 
effective repressive operations by the Peruvian Air Force (FAP), 
which operated with the support of U.S. radar installations. 
  Opposition Legislator Julio Castro Gomez has stated that if 
the current level of trafficking flights is maintained, it will 
reach 10,000 by the end of the year. 
  With each flight, the Colombian drug "cartels" transport 
guns 
and money to Peru in exchange for cocaine paste which is later 
transformed into cocaine hydrochloride in Colombian laboratories. 
  Castro Gomez stated that according to official sources, the 
Colombian planes transport between 1,300 to 1,500 metric tons of 
cocaine paste per year, and leave in Peru somewhere between $1.5 
and $2 billion. 
  Trafficking has been back to normal since May when the U.S. 
Government closed down the only fixed radar it operated in Peru. 
It also decided to suspend flights of its AWACS E-3 and Orion 
P-3 planes, equipped with modern flight detection equipment. 
  The U.S. withdrawal, which took Peruvian officials by 
surprise, compelled the Peruvian Government to issue a formal 
protest. They reasserted, however, their firm political 
willingness to continue the antidrug struggle with their own 
resources. 
  Achieving this goal is, however, very difficult because Peru 
lacks the indispensable economic and material means to stop the 
shipments. 
  A high-ranking FAP official has stated that the U.S. 
decision 
"has left us virtually blind. We are frustrated because drug 
traffickers are flying right under our noses and we are unable 
to do anything about it." 
  The same source noted that the only means available to the 
FAP to combat the drug cargoes are four battered T-27 planes, 
two helicopters, and eventually, two more A-37 planes. 
  By comparison, the traffickers are equipped with modern 
planes that can easily dodge FAP planes and make night flights 
with special equipment. 
  The military source stated: "A T-37 flies at 200 knots and 
at 
26,000 feet, while drug mafia planes reach 300 knots and 30,000 
feet." 
  A U.S. technical mission arrived last week in Peru to 
explain 
the reasons for withdrawing its logistic air support. The result 
of the negotiations have been kept strictly secret. 
  The Peruvian press reported, nevertheless, that U.S. support 
was suspended for fear of legal complications for the United 
States in the event of a downing of a civilian plane "by 
mistake." 
  This comes following a recent experience in which a U.S. 
warplane mistakenly shot down two U.S. helicopters in Iraq. 
  The FAP spokesperson stated that U.S. Government's concern 
does not apply in Peru's case because experience has shown that 
the FAP complies with international regulations for the 
interception of planes. 
  He said: "When we intercept a plane we comply with the steps 
of verification, identification, and communication. Only then, 
and if it refuses to comply with orders, do we fire at nonvital 
parts of the plane and, as a last resort, shoot it down." 
  The Peruvian press has reported that it seems the United 
States wants to establish "specific legal guidelines" under 
which Peru will assume full responsibility if a civilian plane 
is mistakenly downed. 
  Some trafficking experts have stated, however, that 
Washington's fears do not justify withdrawing U.S. air logistics 
support from Peru. They added that the U.S. decision "causes 
doubts about its political willingness to combat the issue." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34709 </DOCNO>
