<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Studies With Canada Under Way for Reactor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Studies With Canada Under Way for Reactor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2306141994 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 22 Jun 94 p 1 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2306141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "special correspondent" Silvia Pisani] </F>
  [Text] Ottawa -- The signing of a nuclear cooperation 
agreement between Argentina and Canada has already got the first 
joint project off the ground. The two countries will begin 
studies for the construction of an energy-producing plant to 
supply a city of 3 million residents. 
  The agreement is one of the key factors in President Carlos 
Menem's trip, and it includes the possible construction of a 
400-megawatt Candu-type unit, which is larger than that of 
Atucha. 
  The studies could be concluded by year's end, and the unit 
will be installed in the neighborhood of the Embalse Nuclear 
Center, in Cordoba Province, if an agreement is reached. The 
Canadians have guaranteed that they are in a position to build 
it in 42 months. There also will be innovations such as the use 
of partially enriched uranium to reduce contamination and 
increase the fuel's yield. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

