<H3> <TI>   Canadian Minister of State Pays Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canadian Minister of State Pays Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Cuban Official Praises Resumption of Aid </H4>

<F P=102> PA2106194094 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1840 GMT 21 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2106194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 21 Jun (PL) -- Today, Cuban Vice Foreign 
Minister Jorge Bolanos said the restoration of Canadian aid to 
Cuba reflects that country's rejection of any measure aimed at 
isolating the nation. 
  We intend to maintain and develop ties between the two 
countries, Bolanos said, adding Cuba is Canada's first trade 
partner in the Caribbean and Central American region. 
  Praising the decision, the Cuban vice foreign minister said 
the resumption of aid, which was suspended in 1978 due to Cuba's 
presence in Angola, opens a new phase in our bilateral 
relations, which "have always been prominent." 
  Bolanos said the main issue in this decision is the 
political 
effect it will have. The formal announcement of the restoration 
of aid to Havana was made in this capital by Christine Stewart, 
Canadian minister of state for Latin America and Africa, who 
spoke against isolating the island. 
  According to Bolanos, Stewart invited, on behalf of Canadian 
Foreign Minister Andre Ouellet, Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina to Ottawa, and the invitation will be honored sometime 
this year. 
  Canada, as Mexico, never severed its commercial or 
diplomatic 
ties with Havana and has expressed opposition to the blockade 
the United States imposed more than 30 years ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

