<H3> <TI>   Rules Against Illegal Enrichment Implemented </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rules Against Illegal Enrichment Implemented </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2106214194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1343 GMT 21 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2106214194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 21 Jun (PL) -- The Cuban Government has 
approved regulations to Law Decree No. 149, which covers the 
confiscation of goods and income obtained through illegal 
enrichment. 
  A Council of Ministers Executive Committee agreement 
establishes the method to be followed in such cases. Already, 
several dozen people have been found to be involved in illegal 
activities regarding the obtainment of goods. Files on these 
individuals have been opened. 
  According to information published by GRANMA today, the 
regulations detail the conditions established for preliminary 
investigations, the resources available for the accused, the 
procedures to review cases, the preventive measures to avoid the 
distribution of stolen goods, and the final destination of 
stolen goods. 
  The document outlines the procedures to be practiced by 
prosecutors, which include the possibility of searching the 
houses of suspects, their relatives, or third parties, as well 
as conducting necessary audits, inventories, and appraisals. 
  After the reform resource and the review procedure, which 
are 
to be presented to Finance and Price Minister, and the final 
ruling on the case, no other process will be established in the 
administrative or judicial sectors. 
  Lastly, the regulations clarify that the organizations in 
charge will be responsible for the preservation, custody, and 
distribution of goods and income that are subject to preventive 
or confiscatory measures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

