<H3> <TI>   U.S. Citizens To Visit, Reject Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Citizens To Visit, Reject Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2306171394 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2306171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "First Thing" program] </F>
  [Text] Approximately 200 U.S. citizens, members of the 
second Freedom to Travel flight, will arrive in Cuba on 23 June 
to visit sites of economic, historic, and social interest. 
These U.S. citizens are exercising their constitutional rights 
to travel anywhere in the world and to reject the blockade 
against Cuba. Freedom to Travel members are challenging a U.S. 
law on visiting Cuba and face a possible 10-year prison term and 
fines of up to $250,000. The first such trip to Havana took 
place in November 1993 and included 165 citizens from over 25 
different U.S. states. This visit is sponsored by the Cuban 
Institute of Friendship with Peoples with the help of the Union 
of Young Communists and the Pablo Milanes Foundation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

