<H3> <TI>   Bank General Manager Stresses Development Potential </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bank General Manager Stresses Development Potential </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2306220894 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 23 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2306220894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Havana, Bert Denker, general manager of the ING 
International Bank in the Netherlands, said the ING Bank chose 
Cuba for its economic activities because it is a country that 
has potential and an appropriate infrastructure for development. 
He said 80 percent of trade with the island consists of basic 
products, and he believes emphasis should be placed on 
investments in areas that generate capital for the country, such 
as exports. He also believes emphasis should be placed on 
production in areas that can substitute for imported products. 
  The general manager of the ING Bank in the Netherlands 
listed 
some of Cuba's assets as: an educational system that guarantees 
a highly skilled work force; huge nickel reserves that can be 
exploited efficiently and at low cost; and an excellent 
reputation in tourist development. 
  Denker is attending the second round table conference with 
the Cuban Government organized by THE ECONOMIST financial 
magazine. The conference, which is being held in Havana, is 
scheduled to last two days. 

</TEXT>

