<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry: Senator Graham Persona Non Grata </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry: Senator Graham Persona Non Grata </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2306215294 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2306215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of 
Haiti has energetically protested the thoughtless statements by 
U.S. Senator Robert Graham on the occasion of his visit to Cite 
Solel on Saturday, 18 May [date as heard]. 
  His statements, the Ministry says, are contrary to all norms 
of international law and can in no way be tolerated by the 
government of the Republic. Mr. Graham's provocation is all the 
more unacceptable in his having taken advantage of the Haitian 
people's hospitality to threaten the sovereignty of this country 
and openly call for its invasion. There is no doubt that Mr. 
Graham's cynical statements lie within the scope of his 
electoral campaign. 
  Following Mr. Graham's unspeakable behavior, the government 
of the Republic of Haiti declares him persona non grata and his 
presence no longer accepted on national territory. 
  The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Haiti 
takes this opportunity to invite foreigners to refrain from 
interfering in Haiti's internal affairs. 
  It should be recalled that Florida Democratic Sen. Bob 
Graham, at the conclusion of a 24-hour visit to Port-au-Prince, 
came out in favor of a multinational military intervention in 
Haiti in case of failure of the international sanctions. He 
asserted that President-in-exile Jean-Bertrand Aristide was 
favorable to that as a necessary last resort. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

