<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas Distributes Land Titles in Tamaulipas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas Distributes Land Titles in Tamaulipas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2306221194 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2306221194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jaime Guerrero from the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Carlos Salinas says the reformation of 
Article No. 27 puts an end to the great Zapatist revolution. He 
said the struggle for land is over and now the battle is for 
production and democracy. 
  The president distributed common land [ejido] titles and 
confirmed the legality of the documents. Thus far this year, 
600,000 peasants have received land titles, thanks to an 
extensive statistical effort to establish boundaries. 
  In Aguascalientes, dozens of peasants gathered to hear 
President Salinas deliver a message of reconciliation. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] The men and women of the 
countryside no longer want to exhaust themselves in conflicts. 
The struggle for land is over, and the victors are the Mexican 
peasants. [end recording] 
  The president said an effort will be made to prevent 
conflicts from eroding agrarian reform. He told the peasants 
who received titles that their agrarian certificates puts an end 
to the Zapatist revolution. The EZLN's lands are legally 
secure, but that is not enough in one of the most backward 
sectors of the economy. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] A struggle is now being waged for 
the peasants to make their own decisions regarding production, 
organization, democracy, and freedom. [end recording] 
  The president's tour was devoted to land ownership. In 
Matamoros, Tamaulipas, the ceremony was very symbolic. Among 
the people who gathered were 11 peasants who descended from the 
group to whom Lucio Blanco in 1913 presented the first plot of 
land resulting from the Mexican Revolution. Eighty-one years 
later, they have titles for their plots. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] We have fulfilled the pledge of 
the government of the Mexican Revolution. [end recording] 
  In this border city the president confirmed his pledge to 
defend the country's sovereignty and independence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

