<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Secretary on Commitment to Open Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Secretary on Commitment to Open Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2306171894 Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 21 Jun 94 p 37 </F>
<F P=103> PA2306171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City LA JORNADA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Relations Secretary Manuel Tello Macias has 
said Mexico has a commitment for legal, open, and credible 
elections in August. Mexico also has a commitment to respond to 
the "powerful dynamics," oppositions, expectations, and 
challenges it faces within the framework of the globalization of 
the economy resulting from participation in NAFTA, APEC 
[Economic Association of Asian and Pacific Nations], and the 
OECD. 
  During the inauguration of the Third Meeting of Honorary 
Mexican Consuls (the previous two meetings were held in 1990 and 
1992), the official said the nation is experiencing important, 
transcendental, historic moments, an accelerated transformation, 
and a process of modernization in all sectors. 
  He said that based on joining NAFTA, APEC, and the OECD, the 
country is now poised as a forerunner within the international 
economic system and has linked up with the world's most dynamic 
trend in economic growth as well as trade and technological 
exchange. 
  Tello told the 56 Mexican honorary consuls that 
domestically, 
with the participation of all the political and social forces, a 
consensus has been reached and mechanisms have been established 
so that this year's elections will be legal, open, and credible. 
  He also spotlighted Mexicans' commitment to firm, unyielding 
democracy, saying: "The electoral competition we are witnessing 
proves this commitment overwhelmingly." 
  At the meeting where four display tables were set up for the 
promotion of image, foreign trade, tourism, consular and 
immigration matters, the consuls were supplied with up-to-date 
material to appropriately promote the nation.x President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari received the officials at the presidential 
residence, Los Pinos, at the end of the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34789 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat122_c_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2406034094 </F>
<F P=103> PA2406034094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
21 August. 
  Ernesto Zedillo, presidential candidate for the 
Institutional 
Revolutionary Party, PRI, presents a 10-point program to combat 
poverty, pledges to continue to implement and decentralize the 
solidarity program, and calls upon all Mexicans to join in the 
fight against poverty. 
  Cuauthemoc Cardenas, presidential candidate for the Party of 
the Democratic Revolution, PRD, finishes a three-day visit to 
Chihuahua State and is criticized by the National Action Party, 
PAN, for his negative comments on PAN Governor Francisco 
Barrios. PAN publicly accuses Cardenas of diverting funds while 
he was governor of Michoacan. 
  National Opposition Union, UNO, candidate Pablo Emilio 
Maderos visits the National Autonomous University of Mexico 
where he pledges to fight unemployment and poverty. 
  Jorge Gonzalez Torres, presidential candidate for the 
Mexican 
Green Ecologist Party, PVEM, visits Oaxaca State, where he says 
the 21 August elections will suffer because of the high level of 
poverty in Mexico. He calls for a peaceful solution to the 
Chiapas conflict because, he says, an armed conflict benefits no 
one. [Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 16 
Jun 94] 
  In Veracruz, Zedillo speaks to thousands of PRI members, 
saying the country's institutional life cannot be negotiated or 
transformed into the political gain of uncompromising 
minorities. He calls upon Mexicans to respect social peace, 
sovereignty, national unity, independence, and freedom. [Mexico 
City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 17 Jun 94 pp 1-5] 
  Rafael Aguilar Talamantes, presidential candidate for the 
Cardenist Front for National Reconstruction, ends his visit to 
several Jalisco municipalities. 
  Labor Party candidate Cecilia Soto holds a news conference 
in 
Reynosa, Tamaulipas State, during which she says that the United 
States should provide Mexico and Colombia with evidence of its 
will to reduce drug use, combat money laundering and arms 
smuggling, and prosecute drug lords in the United States. 
[Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 17 Jun 
94] 
  Cardenist Front candidate Aguilar Talamantes says Peace 
Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis' resignation is good for the 
country and that his party and the Zapatist National Liberation 
Army, EZLN, are both fighting for the same improvements. [Mexico 
City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 20 
Jun 94] 
  During an interview, PRD candidate Cardenas pledges to 
improve Mexico's education system and says there is still time 
to make electoral reforms. [Mexico City XEW Television Network 
in Spanish 0430 GMT 21 Jun 94] 
  PRI candidate Zedillo admits that problems in the electoral 
process have made would-be voters distrustful. He invites PRI 
businessmen and intellectuals to attend meetings on his behalf 
because such meetings would lend legitimacy to his probable 
victory. [Monterrey EL NORTE (Foreign Edition) in Spanish 21 Jun 
94 p 1A] 
  Zedillo campaigns in Villa Alvaro Obregon, a Mexico City 
low-income neighborhood where he reiterates his pledge to combat 
excessive poverty. In Mexico City, Labor Party candidate Soto 
calls for reforming the power of the president. [Mexico City 
Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0140 GMT 22 Jun 94] 
  A new group called the Citizen's Network has been created to 
promote peace during the elections. The PRD calls for an 
amendment to the Electoral Law, but the PRI disagrees. Zedillo 
says the people, not the government, own the solidarity program 
because the people pay for it. PAN presidential candidate Diego 
Fernandez de Cevallos denies that his campaign has slowed down, 
saying that he stopped visiting small communities only because 
such visits make him lose sight of the larger picture. Labor 
Party candidate Soto proposes a women's secretariat and claims 
that she is the victim of slander on the part of her opponents. 
[Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 22 Jun 
94] 
  The Federal Electoral Institute, IFE, reports that foreign 
visitors will be allowed to observe the coming August elections 
as a means of eliminating suspicions of fraud but the visitors 
will be banned from participating in political activities. IFE 
reports that the 48 million ballots required for the coming 
elections have been sent to the states. Zedillo holds a meeting 
at the Change 21 Foundation, where he says it is necessary to 
create a new federalism. In Toluca, Labor Party candidate Soto 
opposes the PRD's proposal to institute the death sentence. 
[Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 
GMT 23 Jun 94] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

