<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Responsibility for Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Denies Responsibility for Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2406040594 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2406040594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The government does not take responsibility for the 
financial crisis the nation is experiencing, because, according 
to Guillermo Alvarez Bajares, OCI [Central Information Office] 
director, the Executive Branch does not have a major say in 
decisions made by the Banking Superintendency and the Central 
Bank of Venezuela. 
  In his statements, which were motivated by the proposed 
censure vote against Finance Minister Julio Sosa, Alvarez 
Bajares said that the responsibility falls on the Congress, 
because the government's legal actions, which are very well 
defined, exclude it from making such decisions. Regardless of 
whether the parliament approves the appointment, it is the 
president who appoints candidates to head these organizations. 
  In the opinion of the OCI director, government officials are 
not implementing decisions of the Fogade [Deposit Guarantee and 
Banking Protection Fund], Banking Superintendency, and Central 
Bank of Venezuela. As a result, contradictions appear in each of 
these institutions. He admitted that the situation is difficult 
to manage. Even though the decision to subsidize the banks was 
made at a cabinet meeting and subsequently sent to the Congress 
for its approval, Alvarez Bajares insisted that the problem 
belongs to the political parties that approved the subsidies and 
now criticize the situation. 
  [Begin Alvarez Bajares recording] Except for the [words 
indistinct] management problem it has inherited and its attempts 
to mitigate the resulting social effects, the government has 
little responsibility for management as far as a decisions made 
on specific issues are concerned. The government does not manage 
monetary policy, it does not manage the amount of subsidies 
granted to banks, and it does not manage or control bank 
operations. 
  The OCI minister reiterated that the government does not 
necessarily agree with policies adopted until now; it is just 
the contrary. The government objects to the high interest rates, 
among other things, but this policy is not the responsibility of 
the Finance Ministry, he noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

