<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas Appoints New Peace Commissioner in Chiapas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas Appoints New Peace Commissioner in Chiapas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2306232794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2158 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2306232794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Mexico City, 23 Jun (EFE) -- Mexican President 
Carlos Salinas de Gortari today appointed Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, 
president of the National Human Rights Committee (CNDH), the new 
commissioner for peace and reconciliation in the State of 
Chiapas, which is in southeastern Mexico. 
  Madrazo Cuellar will replace Manuel Camacho Solis, who 
resigned 16 June claiming that his work had been criticized by 
Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon, presidential candidate of the 
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party. 
  "The government's purpose has been clear: to transform the 
armed conflict into a political dialogue, which will overcome 
differences," Salinas said upon announcing the appointment of 
Madrazo Cuellar, who will ask the Senate for a leave of absence 
to quit the CNDH. [passage omitted] 
  Salinas said the measures adopted by the government, 
including an amnesty law, a cease-fire, and the creation of the 
post of peace commissioner in January, were to "try to resolve 
within the framework of the law" the demands for dialogue in San 
Cristobal, 780 km southeast of the Mexican capital. 
  "It is not through violence that one achieves democratic 
progress, welfare, and justice. We are committed to having 
Mexico grow in peace, with more justice and sovereignty," the 
Mexican president stated. The government is determined to make 
additional efforts to maintain the dialogue and promote a 
political solution to the conflict, he said. He recognized that 
the political parties are committed to the advancement of 
democracy. 
  Camacho Solis was appointed by Salinas on 10 January to find 
political solutions to the Indian insurrection that broke out on 
1 January in Chiapas. Camacho Solis met with the rebels between 
23 February and 3 March in San Cristobal de las Casas to offer 
solutions to their demands. Despite the cease-fire that has 
been in effect since 12 January, the conflict in Chiapas is at 
an impasse after the Zapatist guerrillas turned down the 
government's offer and ended their dialogue with the government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34835 </DOCNO>
