<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2306235594 </F>
<F P=103> PY2306235594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 23 June. 
  The World Bank and the International Development Association 
have granted $860 million to Bolivia over the past few years, of 
which $210 has been repaid, while the remaining $650 million 
will be paid back over the next 40 years. (La Paz HOY in 
Spanish 9 Jun 94 p 17) 
  On 15 June in Rome, the International Fund for Agricultural 
Development and the Bolivian Government signed a 7.6 million 
loan agreement designed to finance a development project for 
llama and alpaca breeders of the Andean Altiplano. The project 
includes 17 provinces in the departments of La Paz, Oruro, and 
Potosi, where 31,700 families are engaged in the breeding of 
llamas and alpacas. (La Paz LA RAZON in Spanish 16 Jun 94 p B8) 
  The Central Bank reported that international reserves had 
risen to $448 million by the first half of June, the highest 
level in the past 14 years. Freely available foreign exchange 
reserves now total $434 million. (Santa Cruz EL MUNDO in 
Spanish 18 Jun 94 National Section p 1) 
  Carlos Vilaseca, president of the National Chamber of 
Customs 
Officers, said on 10 June that customs revenues registered a 
$200 million deficit last year as a result of the illegal 
smuggling of merchandise, which amounted to $800 million. 
During the Eighth Congress of Customs Officers, Vilaseca 
charged that customs officials carry out joint operations with 
smugglers, to whom they grant protection. (La Paz LA RAZON in 
Spanish 11 Jun 94 p B4) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

