<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lula Discusses Military `Redemocratization' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lula Discusses Military `Redemocratization' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2406023894 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 23 Jun 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PY2406023894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By special correspondent Jose Luiz Longo from Cape Town, </F>
South Africa] 
  [Text] The military issue was at the center of a meeting 
held yesterday by PT [Workers Party] presidential candidate Luiz 
Inacio Lula da Silva and Minister Jay Naidoo, the coordinator of 
the South African social reform program. Lula voiced concern 
over the redemocratization of the Armed Forces. He said he 
intends to set up rules based on constitutional provisions in 
coordination with military commanders. 
  Lula expressed his concern about redemocratizing the Armed 
Forces when Naidoo alluded to the extreme care with which the 
South African Government is addressing the issue, taking into 
account that security in South Africa continues to remain 
exclusively in the hands of the white minority. 
  Lula acknowledged that the situation in the Brazilian Armed 
Forces is different, because they have fewer resources than the 
South African military, whose budget will have to be streamlined 
to allow the government to increase investments in social areas. 
  Lula said: In our case, our military even have financial 
problems in procuring polish for their boots. Yet we share the 
same concern about democratizing the Armed Forces. 
  Before having dinner with Naidoo -- a former president of 
COSATU [Congress of South African Trade Unions], a trade union 
organization similar to CUT [Sole Workers Center] in Brazil -- 
Lula said he hopes to have the support of trade union 
organizations, especially CUT, to give greater dynamics to 
government-labor-management committees if he is elected 
president. 
  Lula said: Government-labor-management committees are 
important tools in relieving unions from merely channeling wage 
demands to addressing issues such as economic growth goals in 
our talks with the government and employers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

