Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reiterates Position on Occupations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reiterates Position on Occupations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2606015594 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 26 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2606015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina reiterated 
the Cuban Government's position to deny departure permits for 
people who forcibly occupy foreign missions. He also denounced 
foreign encouragement of the actions. 
  The Cuban foreign minister made the statements during a 
meeting with members of the Freedom To Travel group, a U.S. 
group that challenges their country's laws by visiting Havana. 
  Robaina told the visitors that all those who occupied the 
Chilean Consulate had already left and that 21 persons remain at 
the German Embassy and another 73 at the Belgian ambassador's 
residence. The foreign minister said that while some people are 
resorting to actions like this, the U.S. Interest Section has 
denied visas for 40,000 applicants. 
  Robaina told the members of the Freedom To Travel group, 
which is made up of some 190 persons from 25 U.S. states, that 
Cuba has a basic sense of responsibility and that is why it 
insists that diplomatic missions be protected and not trespassed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

